.TH REDUMPER 1 "@DATE@" "redumper @TAG@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
redumper \- low-level byte-perfect optical disc dumper
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B redumper
.RI [ command ]
.RI [ options ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B redumper
is a low-level disc dumper for CD, DVD, HD-DVD and Blu-ray. It supports
incremental dumps, advanced SCSI/C2 error repair, audio CD offset
detection on good PLEXTOR / LG / ASUS / LITE-ON drives, and XGD
(Xbox/Xbox 360) dumping via Kreon custom-firmware drives. It is one of
the dumpers used by the Redump and No-Intro preservation projects.
.PP
Run without arguments,
.B redumper
behaves as
.BR "redumper disc" :
it auto-selects the first drive with a disc inserted, generates an
image name based on the current date and drive name, and produces the
full set of Redump-style dump files.
.SH COMMANDS
A subset of commonly used commands. Run
.B redumper --help
for the full list.
.TP
.B disc
Default. Full dump pipeline: dump, protection scan, split, info.
.TP
.B dump
Raw sector-level read pass only. Used standalone for drive evaluation
or to iterate dump quality with different drives.
.TP
.B split
Split a previously dumped image into Redump-style track files using
TOC or subchannel-Q methods.
.TP
.B info
Generate the Redump submission summary text from an existing dump.
.TP
.B drive::test
Automated probing of a GENERIC drive for sector order, lead-in /
lead-out depth, and read-method support (BE, BE CDDA, D8). Useful when
adapting an unknown drive for CD work.
.TP
.B flash::mt1339
Re-flash drive firmware on MT1339-chipset drives (e.g.\& TS-H353C).
.B Dangerous \(em
no firmware compatibility check is performed; mismatched firmware can
permanently brick the drive.
.SH LINUX DRIVE SYNTAX
On Linux,
.B redumper
addresses drives by their
.B generic SCSI
device node, not the block node:
.PP
.RS
.EX
redumper --drive=/dev/sg1
.EE
.RE
.PP
Use
.I /dev/sg*
(generic SCSI), not
.IR /dev/sr* .
The drive must be writable from the user's perspective because vendor
SCSI commands that alter drive state (speed setting, mode pages) are
issued during a dump \(em this is not the same as burning, the disc is
not written.
.PP
The disc must be
.B unmounted
before
.B redumper
is started. Disabling removable-media automount in the desktop session
is recommended.
.PP
Drive auto-detection may not work on every distribution; if so, pass
.B --drive
explicitly.
.SH DRIVE ACCESS
.B redumper
ships with the
.B cap_sys_rawio
file capability set, so vendor SCSI passthrough commands (Plextor read
method D8, Kreon XGD commands, etc.) work without root.
.PP
The invoking user still needs read/write access to the
.I /dev/sg*
device node. On a desktop session at the local seat, this is granted
automatically via systemd-logind's
.B uaccess
ACL. For headless use (SSH, cron, systemd
.BR \-\-user ,
NFS-mounted device nodes) the user must additionally be a member of
the
.B cdrom
group:
.PP
.RS
.EX
sudo usermod -aG cdrom $USER
newgrp cdrom
.EE
.RE
.SH SUPPORTED DRIVES
Fully supported and recommended for CD work: known-good PLEXTOR, LG,
ASUS and LITE-ON models. For DVD/HD-DVD/Blu-ray any modern drive
generally works.
.PP
For XGD (Xbox / Xbox 360 DVD): a Kreon custom-firmware drive is
required \(em retail firmware drives cannot dump XGD.
.PP
GENERIC drive support exists but does not guarantee a Redump-perfect
CD dump. The README contains a manual evaluation guide for testing
unknown drives.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Dump the inserted disc using the first auto-detected drive:
.B redumper
.TP
Dump using a specific drive, named output:
.B "redumper --drive=/dev/sg1 --image-name=mygame"
.TP
Re-split an existing dump:
.B "redumper split --image-name=mygame"
.TP
Probe an unknown drive's capabilities (insert a mixed-mode CD first):
.B "redumper drive::test --speed=8"
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /usr/bin/redumper
The binary itself, with
.B cap_sys_rawio=ep
preset.
.TP
.I /usr/share/doc/redumper/README.md
Upstream documentation \(em includes the full GENERIC drive evaluation
guide, dump-state details and the complete command reference.
